The tenden- cies os the traditional Roman past were by them utterly disre- garded.= Inspiration was drawn from the stirring lise into which they were plunged, as well as from the sympathetic study of the sources os poetic art among both the earlier Greeks and the Alexandriana As was to be expected, their models of rhythm were not the rude hexameters and ruder Saturnians of their Roman predecessors, but the more polished versification ol the Greeks ; and their subjects were sometimes their own personal experiences and emotions, and sometimes themes sug- gested by their Greek prototypes. So a new school os Roman poetry arose and flourished, to be superseded in turn by the polished Augustans, who cultivated the niceties of elegance, but at the expense ol verva.

It is possible to know him per- sonally as only now and then an ancient writer can be known to us, and yet he gives us but few definite biographical facts concerning himself, while still sewer are given by other authors os his own and later ages, But the little body of poems that constitute his extant works is so replete with his intense person· ality, and shows lorth so unreservedly his every emotion, that the man stands out before us as does no other man ol the age with the exception of two or three ol its political leaders. And all this is true, even though we acknowledge‚ as we are bound to do, thatin many questions of importance concerning his lise we must be content with aworking hypothesis instead os a series of established facts, and that the biographer, as the interpreter of the poems of CatulluS, must be understood to be presenting probabilities, and not certainties.
